'''HMCS ''Edmonton''''' is a {{sclass-|Kingston|coastal defence vessel|1}} that has served in the [[Canadian Forces]] since 1997. ''Edmonton'' is the fourth ship of its class, all of which were built for the [[Maritime Coastal Defence Vessel Project]]. The ship is the first vessel to use the designation HMCS ''Edmonton''.<ref name=l1/> The ship is assigned to [[Maritime Forces Pacific]] (MARPAC) and is homeported at [[CFB Esquimalt]].

==Design and description==
The ''Kingston'' class was designed to fill the [[minesweeper]], coastal patrol and reserve training needs of the Canadian Forces, replacing the {{sclass2-|Bay|minesweeper|1}}s, {{sclass2-|Porte|gate vessel}}s and [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] coastal launches in those roles.<ref name=mac299>Macpherson and Barrie, p. 299</ref> In order to perform these varied duties the ''Kingston''-class vessels are designed to carry up to three {{convert|6.1|m|ft|adj=on}} [[Intermodal container|ISO containers]] with power hookups on the open deck aft in order to embark mission-specific payloads.<ref name=Janes08.09>Saunders (2008), p. 95</ref> The seven module types available for embarkation include four route survey, two mechanical minesweeping and one bottom inspection modules.<ref name=mac299/>

The ''Kingston'' class [[Displacement (ship)|displace]] {{convert|970|LT|t}} and are {{convert|55.3|m|ftin}} [[Length overall|long overall]] with a [[Beam (nautical)|beam]] {{convert|11.3|m|ftin}} and a [[Draft (hull)|draught]] of {{convert|3.4|m|ftin}}.<ref name=mac299/> The coastal defence vessels are powered by four [[Jeumont-Schneider|Jeumont]] ANR-53-50 alternators coupled to four [[Wärtsilä]] UD 23V12 [[diesel engine]]s creating {{convert|7.2|MW}}. Two LIPS Z-drive [[azimuth thruster]]s are driven by two Jeumont CI 560L motors creating {{convert|3000|hp|lk=in}} and the Z drives can be rotated 360°. This gives the ships a maximum speed of {{convert|15|kn|lk=in}} and a range of {{convert|5000|nmi|lk=in}} at {{convert|8|kn}}.<ref name=saunders2004>Saunders (2004), p. 92</ref> 

The ''Kingston'' class is equipped with a [[Kelvin Hughes]] navigational radar using the I band and a Kelvin Hughes 6000 surface search radar scanning the E and F bands. The vessels carry an AN/SQS-511 towed side scan sonar for minesweeping and a Remote-control Mine Hunting System (RMHS). The vessels are equipped with one [[Bofors 40 mm gun|Bofors 40 mm/60 calibre Mk 5C gun]] and two [[M2 Browning machine gun|M2 machine gun]]s.<ref name=saunders2004/>{{efn| name = gun nomenclature}} The ''Kingston''-class coastal defence vessels have a complement of 37.<ref name=mac299/>

==Service history==
''Edmonton'' was [[Keel laying|laid down]] on 8 August 1995 by [[Halifax Shipyards|Halifax Shipyards Ltd.]] at [[Halifax, Nova Scotia]], and was [[Ship naming and launching|launched]] on 31 October 1996. The ship underwent [[sea trials]] on the east coast before transferring to the [[British Columbia coast|west coast]], accompanied by {{HMCS|Moresby|MSA 112|2}}. The vessel was [[Ship commissioning|commissioned]] into the Canadian Forces on 21 May 1997 at [[Esquimalt, British Columbia]] and carries the [[Hull classification symbol (Canada)|hull number]] MM 703.<ref name=mac300>Macpherson and Barrie, p. 300</ref>

In June-July 2002, ''Edmonton'' and [[sister ship]]s {{HMCS|Nanaimo|MM 702|2}} and {{HMCS|Saskatoon|MM 709|2}} participated in the naval exercise [[Exercise RIMPAC|RIMPAC 2002]] off [[Hawaii]].<ref name=mac300/>

In February 2016 ''Edmonton'' and {{HMCS|Saskatoon|MM 709|2}} sailed from Esquimalt to join [[Operation Caribbe]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.timescolonist.com/news/local/esquimalt-based-naval-vessels-join-operation-caribbe-1.2172150 |title=Esquimalt-based naval vessels join Operation Caribbe |work=Times Colonist |date=12 February 2016 |accessdate=17 February 2016}}</ref> On 25 March, in conjunction with the [[United States Navy]] [[destroyer]] {{USS|Lassen|DDG-82|2}}, ''Edmonton'' intercepted drug smugglers in international waters off the coast of Central America. After being stopped the smuggling vessel attempted to dump its cargo overboard. ''Edmonton'', working with a [[United States Coast Guard]] detachment, recovered 27 bales of [[cocaine]] equaling {{convert|650|kg|lb}}.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://ottawacitizen.com/news/national/defence-watch/more-drug-seizures-for-her-majestys-canadian-ships-saskatoon-and-edmonton |title=More drug seizures for Her Majesty’s Canadian Ships Saskatoon and Edmonton |work=Ottawa Citizen |last=Pugliese |first=David |date=8 April 2016 |accessdate=17 April 2016}}</ref> ''Edmonton'' and ''Saskatoon'' returned to Esquimalt on 29 April 2016.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cheknews.ca/shawnigan-protesters-greet-defence-minister-as-hmcs-edmonton-saskatoon-come-home-170044/ |title=Shawnigan protesters greet defence minister as HMCS Edmonton, Saskatoon come home |newspaper=CHEK News |last=van Straaten |first=Tess |date=29 April 2016 |accessdate=6 May 2016}}</ref> On 6 October, {{HMCS|Brandon|MM 710|2}} and ''Edmonton'' left Esquimalt to participate in Operation Caribbe along the Pacific coast.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://ottawacitizen.com/news/national/defence-watch/three-royal-canadian-navy-ships-to-take-part-in-counter-drug-operation |title=Three Royal Canadian Navy ships to take part in counter-drug operation |newspaper=Ottawa Citizen |last=Pugliese |first=David |date=6 October 2016 |accessdate=7 October 2016}}</ref>

